\begin_layout Standard
Stein's method is motivated by the idea of a characterizing operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fo$
\end_inset

 be a vector space and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xo$
\end_inset

 be a vector space of measurable functions which contains the constant functions.
 We say a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\To:\Fo\to\Xo$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
characterizing operator
\emph default
 for the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lo$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\im\To=\Xo\cap\ker\Eo$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience, where there is no ambiguity we will often implicitly restrict
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Eo$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xo$
\end_inset

, so we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\im\To=\ker\Eo$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following proposition shows why 
\begin_inset Formula $\To$
\end_inset

 is called a characterizing operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:characterizing"

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\To:\Fo\to\Xo$
\end_inset

 is a characterizing operator and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xo$
\end_inset

 is a determining class then 
\begin_inset Formula $\im\To\subseteq\ker\E_{\X}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}=\Lo$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\h\in\Xo$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\h-\Eo\h\in\ker\Eo=\im\To$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{\X}\left[\h-\Eo\h\right]=0$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{\X}\h=\Eo\h$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\h\in\Xo$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $\L{\X}=\Lo$
\end_inset

 by the definition of a determining class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:U_0-characterizing"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\To:\Fo\to\Xo$
\end_inset

 is characterizing if and only if there is a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Uo:\Xo\to\Fo$
\end_inset

 (called a 
\emph on
Stein transform
\emph default
) such that the following two equations hold.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Eo\To & =0_{\Fo},\label{eq:E_0T_0-consistency}\\
\To\Uo+\Eo & =\id_{\Xo}.\label{eq:U_0-characterizing}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\To$
\end_inset

 is a characterizing operator.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E_0T_0-consistency"

\end_inset

 is immediate.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \h_{\i}\right\} _{\i\in\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

 be a (Hamel) basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xo$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\i\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\h_{\i}-\Eo\h_{\i}\in\ker\Eo$
\end_inset

 so there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $\fo_{\i}$
\end_inset

 (not necessarily unique) that solves 
\begin_inset Formula $\To\fo_{\i}=\h_{\i}-\Eo\h_{\i}$
\end_inset

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Uo$
\end_inset

 can then be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\i\in\mathcal{I}}a_{\i}\h_{\i}\mapsto\sum_{\i\in\mathcal{I}}a_{\i}\fo_{\i}$
\end_inset

, satisfying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U_0-characterizing"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E_0T_0-consistency"

\end_inset

 holds and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Uo$
\end_inset

 exists satisfying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U_0-characterizing"

\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\h\in\ker\Eo$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\To\left(\Uo\h\right)=\h$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\h\in\im\To$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\Eo\subseteq\im\To$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E_0T_0-consistency"

\end_inset

 immediately says that 
\begin_inset Formula $\im\To\subseteq\ker\Eo$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\To$
\end_inset

 is a characterizing operator.
\end_layout

